  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Who are some great but lesser known female Indian freedom fighters?",
  "response": "While many are familiar with iconic figures like Rani Lakshmi Bai and Sarojini Naidu, there were numerous other women who played crucial roles in India's struggle for independence but remain lesser known. Here are some of these remarkable yet underrecognized female Indian freedom fighters:\n\n1. **Matangini Hazra**:\n   - Known as \"Gandhi Buri\" (Old Lady Gandhi), Hazra was an active participant in the Quit India Movement of 1942. At the age of 73, she led a procession of around 6,000 volunteers towards the Tamluk police station and court house, carrying the Indian flag and shouting \"Vande Mataram.\" She was shot multiple times by the British police but continued to march forward until she succumbed to her injuries.\n\n2. **Kanaklata Barua**:\n   - A young Assamese freedom fighter, Barua led the Mrityu Bahini (Suicide Squad) at the age of 17 during the Quit India Movement. On September 20, 1942, she led a procession to hoist the Indian flag at the Gohpur police station in Assam. She was shot dead by the police but became a symbol of courage and sacrifice.\n\n3. **Usha Mehta**:\n   - A Gandhian and freedom fighter, Mehta is best known for her role in organizing the Congress Radio, also known as the Secret Congress Radio, during the Quit India Movement. Broadcasting from an underground station, she played a critical role in disseminating news and messages during a period when the British had imposed a strict media blackout.\n\n4. **Accamma Cherian**:\n   - Known as the \"Jhansi Rani of Travancore,\" Cherian was a prominent leader in Kerala. She was instrumental in leading the Vimochana Samaram (Liberation Struggle) against the autocratic rule of C.P. Ramaswamy Iyer, the Diwan of Travancore. Her fearless participation in the Quit India Movement and her role in mobilizing women are noteworthy.\n\n5. **Tara Rani Srivastava**:\n   - Srivastava was an active member of the Indian National Congress and played a significant role in the Quit India Movement. She was arrested multiple times for her involvement in protests and demonstrations. Her husband, Phoolan Prasad, was also a freedom fighter, and together, they contributed significantly to the cause of independence.\n\n6. **Parvati Giri**:\n   - Also known as \"Mother of the Freedom Movement in Odisha,\" Giri played a vital role in mobilizing women in the independence movement. She was involved in the Salt Satyagraha and other significant protests against British rule, inspiring countless others to join the struggle.\n\nThese women, among many others, made immense sacrifices and contributions to India's fight for freedom, yet their stories often remain in the shadows of more prominent figures. Their courage and dedication deserve to be remembered and celebrated.",
